AGI -&nbsp;In a context characterized by a "considerable increase in cyber threat">, in 2023 the Csirt (Computer security response team Italy) of the National Cybersecurity Agency > treated 1.411 events, almost 4 per day, one every 6 hours but above all 29% more '> than the 1.094 of the previous year; 303 those classified as "indents with confirmed impact", 140.5% more, and 3.302 target subjects, 187.1% more. It is an alarming scenario designed in the Annual Report to the Parliament by the Acn. From the dossier - 121 pages and seven sections rich in numbers and analyses - emerges a sensitive increase of the reports addressed to the Agency (349 in front of the 81 of the previous year, +330.9%) while the requests for information increased (+10.8%). Monitored 3.624 risk assets (+37.3%), 56 ransomware actors and 265 hacktivists: 584 phishing attempts reported to the victims. Also in 2023 were 3,302 Italian subjects targeting cyber events > identified by Csirt, in the face of the 1,150 of 2022: their increase - the report explains - is "to be subscribed to the increase of the ability to monitor Acn, which now allow to identify, in addition to the potentially compromised assets, even the potentially vulnerable ones". All this is accompanied by the agency's activities to report any compromises or risk factors to monitored subjects. This is through the public portal, both through the collaboration portal with private access, where, in particular, alerts and newsletters are almost doubled (+89.5%). &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Each of the cyber events may have been associated with one or more types: For example, a phishing event is often aimed at spreading malware, which can be a ransomware-type event. The most common types of attack are DDos (319 cases), malware via email (275), phishing (240), ransomware (165), brand abuse (159) and others. With regard to the areas of activity of the target parties, telecommunications and public administration prevail, both locally and centrally. To correctly interpret the data, it is worth noting that each event can be associated with one or more sectors of activity: telecommunications (216), central public administration (201), local public administration (140), transport (115), financial services (81), technology (75), energy (68), university and research (41), healthcare (40) and others.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
And as "for a large part of Western nations, even for Italy 2023 was a year of heavy and diversified cyber security attacks, > which often proceeded in parallel to the ongoing conflicts in Ukraine and the Middle East". Acn reiterates that "the shift of our lives in cyberspace, especially after the massive use of virtual space during the pandemic, has increased the danger of hostile actors, and on several occasions has put at risk the possibility" for citizens to enjoy essential services, 'firstly' health services". In a scenario of this type, "to secure the national interests in the cyber field requires high technical and strategic capabilities, which face the increasingly devastating use of technology by both state or parastat bodies that have opposing interests to ours, either criminal gangs or individual hackers." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"The sharpening of geopolitical tensions, relating both to the continuing war between Russia and Ukraine and to the change of balances in the Middle East as a result of the Hamas attacks against Israel, have seen the rise of a cyber phenomenon before that very little significant: cyber activism". The National Cybersecurity Agency explains how "groups that aim to support the cause of one of the conflicting parties through malicious cyber actions with clearly visible impacts, later claimed by the group."
&nbsp;
These are mainly DDoS-type events at the detriment of public administration and business websites and, in small numbers (24 events), 'defacement' type, i.e. computer intrusions that consist of changing web pages - usually obsolete and unprotected -, replacing them with a message of claim, apology and similar. Precisely because of the cyber activism linked to current conflicts, there has been a significant increase in DDoS events: in 2023 319, 625% more than 2022. Most events (248) were claimed by pro-Russian collectives, while a pro-Palestinian group conducted a single campaign with 15 DDoS attacks. The remaining DDoS events, "not being claimed, can not be associated with specific compañeros or re-linked to current conflicts." From the monitoring of platforms used by attackers for the claims of DDoS events, it has been found that Italy is the sixth country in the world most affected by these events and the third among EU countries.
&nbsp;
In 2023, the National Cybersecurity Agency managed 422 cyber events to damage national public institutions, > a significant increase (+163%) compared to 160 of the previous year. Of these events, 85 were classified as accidents (in 2022 were 57), procuring in most cases system malfunction and resulting in blockages or slowdowns in service delivery. The Agency's Annual Report, presented this morning: considering the frequency and impact - an average of more than one incident per week> - of the different types of events, it emerges that last year the DDoS was the most frequent phenomenon towards public institutions, followed by the exploitation of vulnerability and phishing. A partial change in route is recorded compared to 2022, when the preponderant threat in public administration was ransomware, followed by DDoS. Among the tasks assigned by law to the Agency are the support of victims of cybersecurity accidents. In more complex cases it can be done through the intervention of a team of specialists (Deployable digital forensic incident response). During the course of 2023, Acn's specialist staff intervened on site in 13 different cases, while in 31 cases it provided remote support alongside targets in the eradication of threat and in the restoration of safety conditions with interventions lasting for several weeks. &nbsp;
